If the PIVOT is slow, you can separate it to 9 different updates wrapped in transaction. Your base query will be:
UPDATE Table1 SET [01] = T2.[Amnt] FROM Table1 T1 INNER JOIN Table2 T2 ON T1.[Desc] = T2.[Desc] WHERE T2.[Week] = '01';
You will do this for each column. If your real example contains bigger number of distinct, weeks, you can use dynamic T-SQL statement to build the execution code. It will be shorter and looks better. Something like this:
DECLARE @DistitincWeeks TABLE ( [Week] VARCHAR(8) ); INSERT INTO @DistitincWeeks ([Week]) SELECT DISTINCT [Week] FROM Table1; DECLARE @DynamictSQLStatement NVARCHAR(MAX) ,@CurrentWeek VARCHAR(8); WHILE(EXISTS(SELECT 1 FROM @DistitincWeeks)) BEGIN; SELECT TOP (1) @CurrentWeek = [Week] FROM @DistitincWeeks; -- SET @DynamictSQLStatement = @DynamictSQLStatement + ' UPDATE Table1 SET [' + @CurrentWeek + '] = T2.[Amnt] FROM Table1 T1 INNER JOIN Table2 T2 ON T1.[Desc] = T2.[Desc] WHERE T2.[Week] = ''' + @CurrentWeek +'''; '; -- DELETE FROM @DistitincWeeks WHERE [Week] @CurrentWeek END; EXECUTE sp_executesql @DynamictSQLStatement;
Alternatively, you can create an after insert trigger on the Table1 which modifies the corresponding rows in Table2 when data is changed. You can use variant of the code above for the trigger body. Just be sure you are manipulating the rows in batches, not in loop or using cursor.
I don't like triggers and will advice if you have a routine, stored procedure or other application code, which is updating the Table1 data, just do update the data in the Table2 , too. It's more clear for me, but you must be sure no other routine is modifying the data in Table1 .
It will be better to constantly updating Table2 on small batches, when data in Table1 is modified against performing huge updates on every X hours or days.
If the following update is slow, too:
UPDATE Table1 SET [01] = T2.[Amnt] FROM Table1 T1 INNER JOIN Table2 T2 ON T1.[Desc] = T2.[Desc] WHERE T2.[Week] = '01';
You should check the table structure (column types) itself and the corresponding indexes.
